  "prompt": "What is the stall speed and AOA of an f-14 with wings fully swept back?",
  "response": "The stall speed and angle of attack (AOA) for the F-14 Tomcat can vary depending on several factors, including weight, configuration, and environmental conditions. However, when the wings are fully swept back (which is typically at 68 degrees), the F-14's stall speed generally increases due to the reduced lift area and altered aerodynamics.\n\n1. **Stall Speed**: For the F-14 with wings fully swept back, the stall speed is approximately around 150 knots (KIAS) under normal conditions. This value can vary with changes in weight and other operational configurations.\n\n2. **Angle of Attack (AOA)**: The stall angle of attack for the F-14 typically occurs at around 25-30 degrees, but again, this can vary depending on the aircraft's configuration and weight.\n\nFor precise numbers, it's essential to refer to the aircraft's specific flight manual or performance charts, as they provide the most accurate information tailored to particular flight conditions.",
